     <div class="commenthead">
      <div class="comment-author vcard">
         <img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/ea5dafa30509fe6c644b611751d65d31?s=36&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D36&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-36 photo' height='36' width='36' />
         <cite class="fn">Ollie Heaviside</cite>      </div>
      

      <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://drop-kicker.com/2014/06/ifind-rf-energy-harvesting-bluetooth-beacon/#comment-5298">June 10, 2014 at 7:22 pm</a>     
           </div>
      <div class="clear"></div>
     
     </div>
     

	<div class="commentbody">
      <p>There’s a simpler way to describe the looming power problem here.  The FCC limits radiated power from *any* household device to less than -42dBm measured at 3 meters.  The ambient RF in most houses is considerably lower than that [about -65dBm at my house.]<br />
The iFind requires an absolute minimum of -9dBm to work.  That&#8217;s over a factor of *a thousand* higher than what&#8217;s allowed in a residence by the FCC [CISPR22 limit lines].<br />
I&#8217;ve posed this concern in their comments, they haven&#8217;t addressed it.  No one seems to think a 2000x error is a problem.  &#8216;They&#8217;ll fix it with innovation somehow.&#8217;  <img src="http://drop-kicker.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" class="wp-smiley" /> </p>

