   <li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-5350">
    
     <div id="comment-5350">
     <div class="commenthead">
      <div class="comment-author vcard">
         <img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/f200bb6088f59fba0e82d90bbf7738ae?s=36&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D36&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-36 photo' height='36' width='36' />
         <cite class="fn">Dave Smart</cite>      </div>
      

      <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://drop-kicker.com/2014/06/ifind-rf-energy-harvesting-bluetooth-beacon/#comment-5350">June 23, 2014 at 3:32 am</a>     
           </div>
      <div class="clear"></div>
     
     </div>
     

	<div class="commentbody">
      <p>I&#8217;ve tried a large number of BLE trackers and even with a proper energy source (battery) the performance is usually terrible, so even if they by some cosmic miracle managed to actually create this wonderful energy harvesting device I would be very skeptical of whether it would perform as promised. Through my testing I found the Philips inRange is the worst of the bunch, followed closely by Stick n Find (both riddled with false alerts). The best performance was from the QL Keyfob which seemed to be the only one that didn&#8217;t constantly false alert, and also had a nice adjustable range feature which &#8211; the only downside was that it wasn&#8217;t the prettiest.</p>

      <div class="reply">
         <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2014/06/ifind-rf-energy-harvesting-bluetooth-beacon/?replytocom=5350#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-5350", "5350", "respond", "1562")'>Reply</a>      </div>
