</li><!-- #comment-## -->
   <li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-5353">
    
     <div id="comment-5353">
     <div class="commenthead">
      <div class="comment-author vcard">
         <img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/b5306a2ba733052efd1a95a9710f2eb1?s=36&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D36&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-36 photo' height='36' width='36' />
         <cite class="fn">Ryan J</cite>      </div>
      

      <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://drop-kicker.com/2014/06/ifind-rf-energy-harvesting-bluetooth-beacon/#comment-5353">June 23, 2014 at 7:54 am</a>     
           </div>
      <div class="clear"></div>
     
     </div>
     

	<div class="commentbody">
      <p>The 10dBm receive power being &#8216;typical for home WiFi&#8217; is very dubious as you pointed out. Here&#8217;s another angle to look at it.</p>
<p>As you mentioned, the maximum transmit power in the 2.4 GHz band is 30 dBm. A radiated signal at a certain frequency will lose power at a predictable rate for a given distance (assuming ideal conditions). This is the &#8216;free space path loss&#8217;. We can use this to work backwards and find out at what distance a 2.4 GHz transmission at +30 dBm would degrade to +10 dBm (a 20 dB path loss).</p>
<p>The answer turns out to be 10 centimeters. Every doubling of the distance introduces an additional 6 dB of path loss. So once we&#8217;re at 160 cm (about 5 feet), we&#8217;re down another 24 dB to -14 dBm. And that&#8217;s under ideal conditions.</p>
<p>/ source for the free space path loss: <a href="http://www.siversima.com/rf-calculator/free-space-path-loss-calculator/" rel="nofollow">http://www.siversima.com/rf-calculator/free-space-path-loss-calculator/</a></p>

      <div class="reply">
         <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2014/06/ifind-rf-energy-harvesting-bluetooth-beacon/?replytocom=5353#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-5353", "5353", "respond", "1562")'>Reply</a>      </div>
     </div>
