   <li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-5367">
    
     <div id="comment-5367">
     <div class="commenthead">
      <div class="comment-author vcard">
         <img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/b7b1d79e5c8dad7344425fa2b7789ee3?s=36&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D36&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-36 photo' height='36' width='36' />
         <cite class="fn">Roger Wolff</cite>      </div>
      

      <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://drop-kicker.com/2014/06/ifind-rf-energy-harvesting-bluetooth-beacon/#comment-5367">June 27, 2014 at 4:48 am</a>     
           </div>
      <div class="clear"></div>
     
     </div>
     

	<div class="commentbody">
      <p>While I agree that this campaign is a fraud, they are making some weird claims. Changing some of the claims might make things more plausible. Not anymore though. </p>
<p>If nokia can harvest 5mW on a 100cm^2 phone, an 8cm^2 tag might be able to harvest 0.5mW. A digital watch runs off about 5uW, so there is quite some margin! Their claim of 36uA is also &#8220;stupid&#8221;. That&#8217;s a lot by modern standards. As I said (and you calculated as well), that&#8217;s about 5 times more than a 20 year old digital watch. Something modern should be able turn at less power than that. Even if you find a chip (accelerometer) that happens to use more, powering it down for say two seconds at a time could reduce energy consumption well below the &#8220;standby current&#8221; in the datasheet. </p>
<p>As to the CPU, an STM32F100 uses 0.3 uA at the deepest sleep I coud find. It doesn&#8217;t have wakeup capabilties then, but it&#8217;s just about 1uA WITH RTC (enough for a timed wakeup). That would come to 3uW with the datasheet conditions. But reducing the core voltage to 1.8V will cut half of the power, and the leakage current will reduce even further below the numbers in the datasheet. I&#8217;m pretty sure some better research than my 20 second google for the low-power version of the  microcontroller I happen to be working with today will turn up something 5-10 times better. </p>
<p>So&#8230; good engineering could produce a device that runs at around 0.1 &#8211; 1 uW, while not transmitting. I don&#8217;t know the power requirements for transmitting bluetooth. But to make this a realistic project, a &#8220;rope interval&#8221; of 10 or 20 seconds should be acceptable. And necessary for energy conservation.  </p>
<p>Another thing: 15mAh is about the size of the whole device. Claim 5mAh and you&#8217;ve made it plausible that it fits in the device with the rest. </p>
<p>And then there is their test&#8230; What I read in their test is that at all distances the battery was draining during their experiment. Completely plausible. And expected. As long as you don&#8217;t promise otherwise, that could be a realistic product&#8230;.</p>

      <div class="reply">
         <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2014/06/ifind-rf-energy-harvesting-bluetooth-beacon/?replytocom=5367#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-5367", "5367", "respond", "1562")'>Reply</a>      </div>
     </div>
     </div>
<ul class="children">
   <li class="comment even depth-2" id="li-comment-5368">
    
     <div id="comment-5368">
     <div class="commenthead">
      <div class="comment-author vcard">
         <img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/46598cebb1e1d5c4237bc36d8d47ae80?s=36&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D36&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-36 photo' height='36' width='36' />
         <cite class="fn"><a href='http://bit.do/ifs' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>DrTune</a></cite>      </div>
      

      <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://drop-kicker.com/2014/06/ifind-rf-energy-harvesting-bluetooth-beacon/#comment-5368">June 27, 2014 at 12:39 pm</a>     
           </div>
      <div class="clear"></div>
     
     </div>
     

	<div class="commentbody">
      <p>Roger you&#8217;re kinda missing the point here; sure there are many embedded CPUs (and accelerometers) now with incredibly low power states; however you didn&#8217;t even look at the Bluetooth power and that&#8217;s the crux of the problem.<br />
You&#8217;re also making the common error of just thinking about transmit; the tag has to be receiving at very regular intervals (every few seconds, let&#8217;s say between 2 &#8211; 15 seconds) to see if it&#8217;s being pinged.<br />
If you look up the datasheets of any BTLE chip (e.g. CC2541) you&#8217;ll see the RX power is barely less than the TX power,  which is in the ballpark of 17ma @ 2v so ~34mw.<br />
It&#8217;s the bluetooth claim which blows everything out of the water (well, that and the fact iFind&#8217;s published numbers were absurd; e.g. the &#8220;10dBm input power to the DC/RF converter&#8221;).</p>
<p>&#8220;Could be a realistic product&#8221; ; nope, not for several different reasons; that&#8217;s why the skeptics laid into them so fiercely.</p>

      <div class="reply">
         <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2014/06/ifind-rf-energy-harvesting-bluetooth-beacon/?replytocom=5368#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-5368", "5368", "respond", "1562")'>Reply</a>      </div>
